-- ── FMD Server ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$FMD Server is the open-source, self-hostable backend for FMD (Find My Device), a privacy-focused Android app that locates, locks, and controls lost devices without relying on Google.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Open Source / Free$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (self-hosted)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(NULL, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$German$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$FMD Server Review 2026: Features, Self-Hosting and Pricing$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$FMD Server is the open-source, self-hosted backend for the Find My Device app. Learn how it works, its encryption model, hosting options, and alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$FMD Server is the self-hostable backend component of FMD, short for Find My Device, an open-source Android application built as a privacy-preserving alternative to Google's Find My Device (now Find Hub) and Apple's Find My. The project is developed by a maintainer known online as Nulide and is distributed through F-Droid, the open-source Android app repository, as well as through GitLab under the fmd-foss organization, which hosts both the FMD Android client and the FMD Server backend as separate repositories. Together the two components let a user locate a lost or stolen Android phone by GPS or cellular positioning, remotely lock it, make it ring, capture a photo from its camera to see its surroundings, and trigger a factory reset, all without any dependency on Google Play Services or a Google account, which makes it particularly popular among users of de-Googled Android distributions such as GrapheneOS and LineageOS, and more generally among privacy-conscious users who do not want their location history flowing through a large commercial platform.

Architecturally, FMD Server is written in Go and stores its data in SQLite, which keeps the resource footprint small; the project publishes three official Docker image variants per release, an Alpine-based image around 55 MB, a Debian-based image around 160 MB, and a distroless image around 40 MB, so operators can choose the trade-off between image size and available debugging tooling. A self-hosted deployment listens for HTTP connections on port 8080 and is expected to sit behind a reverse proxy that terminates TLS, with the SQLite database directory mounted to a host volume so data survives container restarts. Beyond the server's own web interface, which lets an owner send commands and view a device's location on a map and any captured photos, FMD also supports a fully offline control channel: sending a specific text message such as 'fmd' to the phone returns a list of available commands over SMS, and all SMS-based commands are gated by a PIN or a whitelist of trusted phone numbers to prevent unauthorized control.

The standout technical feature of FMD Server is its approach to end-to-end confidentiality and integrity. Location data uploaded by the FMD Android app is protected using an RSA-3072 keypair, with the private key itself protected under an Argon2id-derived AES-GCM key, meaning the server only ever stores ciphertext. In practice this means that even the person or organization operating a given FMD Server instance cannot read a user's location history or photos without the user's own password, and cannot issue valid commands to the device without that same credential, an explicit zero-knowledge design choice that differentiates FMD from many commercial 'find my phone' services where the platform operator can, in principle, access location data server-side.

As an open-source project rather than a company, FMD Server has no publicly disclosed founding year, employee count, or headquarters in the conventional startup sense; it is community-maintained software licensed under GPLv3-or-later, with FMD Android likewise published under an open-source license. This means the primary 'pricing' consideration for FMD Server is infrastructure and operational cost rather than a software license fee: self-hosting on a personal VPS or home server costs nothing beyond hosting, and for people who do not want to manage a server themselves, third-party providers have built managed-hosting offerings on top of the open-source project. DANIAN, for example, advertises a fully managed FindMyDeviceServer instance starting at roughly EUR 9 per month that bundles automated backups, SSL, updates, monitoring, and human support, and packaged versions of FMD Server are also available through app marketplaces such as Cloudron and one-click deployment platforms like Hostinger's application catalog and Dokploy templates, lowering the technical bar for non-experts who still want to avoid depending on Google.

FMD Server's target audience is therefore split between two overlapping groups: technically capable self-hosters who run the Docker image themselves on infrastructure they already control, and privacy-motivated but less technical users who are willing to pay a small monthly fee to a third-party managed-hosting provider in exchange for not having to operate a server. Both groups are typically motivated by the same underlying goal, keeping 'find my phone' functionality working on a de-Googled or privacy-hardened Android device, which is a real gap left open once Google Play Services (and by extension Google's own Find My Device network) is removed from a phone. Within that niche, FMD's most direct competitors are other self-hosted device-tracking and remote-management tools such as Nextcloud's Phone Track app and various open-source anti-theft projects, while its indirect competitors are the built-in platform services it is explicitly designed to replace, Google Find Hub and Apple Find My, which offer broader device support and tighter OS integration but require trusting the platform vendor with location data. FMD's differentiation is its combination of a genuinely open-source, auditable codebase, a self-hostable server component, dual control paths over both the internet and SMS (useful when a lost device has no data connection), and an explicit end-to-end encryption design intended to keep even the server operator out of the loop on a user's location and images.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'a27aac5d-ba7b-4216-98f7-3b5ba2d3cd80';

