-- ── Folk ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Folk is a Paris-based, spreadsheet-style CRM built around a Chrome extension for one-click contact capture and AI-powered enrichment, aimed at small teams managing relationships in sales, recruiting, and fundraising.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Subscription$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$$24/month per member (billed annually)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2020, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Paris, France$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$French$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Folk CRM Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Folk is a lightweight CRM for small teams with an AI-powered LinkedIn extension. Compare Folk's features, exact pricing tiers, pros, cons, and alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Folk is a customer relationship management platform built in Paris that positions itself as a lighter, more modern alternative to traditional CRMs like Salesforce or HubSpot, aimed specifically at small teams of roughly 20 to 50 people who manage relationships across sales, recruiting, fundraising, and partnerships from a single shared workspace. The company was founded in 2020 by Thibaud Elziere, Jean-Yves Poilleux, and Simo Lemhandez, incubated within eFounders, the Paris-based startup studio that has since rebranded as Hexa and that has spun up a number of other B2B SaaS companies. Folk publicly emerged from stealth with a EUR 2.8 million seed round in September 2021, led by Accel alongside a group of roughly 35 angel investors; some funding databases record the same or a closely related round in different currency terms (reported variously as being in the $3.3 million to $4.5 million range depending on the source and conversion date), but the September 2021 Accel-led seed is the consistently documented milestone in press coverage. Public records do not show a subsequent priced round after that seed as of this writing, and Folk has not disclosed a specific employee headcount, though its own marketing repeatedly frames its ideal customer as a team in the 20-to-50-person range, which gives a rough sense of the company's own likely scale as a comparably sized startup.

Product-wise, Folk's core design decision is to represent contacts, companies, and opportunities in spreadsheet-style views called Tables that can be freely grouped, filtered, and sorted by any field, rather than forcing users into the rigid record-and-pipeline structure of a conventional CRM. Pipelines, deals, and campaigns are layered on top of that flexible table structure instead of being the primary organizing concept, which the company argues makes Folk faster to set up and easier to customize for use cases CRM vendors did not anticipate, such as investor relationship tracking for a fundraising round or candidate pipelines for recruiting. The most distinctive feature of the product is folkX, a Chrome browser extension that lets a user add a contact to their Folk workspace with one click directly from LinkedIn, Gmail, Crunchbase, X (formerly Twitter), and dozens of other web pages; captured contacts are then enriched automatically using AI-driven data providers that pull in fields like email address, phone number, job title, company, and industry, similar in spirit to enrichment services such as Clearbit, People Data Labs, or Apollo, reducing the manual data entry that is typically the biggest adoption barrier for CRM tools. Around that core, Folk layers pipeline management, email campaign and sequence tooling, AI assistants for drafting follow-ups, 'Magic Fields' that use AI to auto-fill custom data columns, and native sync with email, calendar, and WhatsApp so that interaction history accumulates automatically rather than requiring manual logging.

Folk's pricing is a straightforward three-tier, per-seat subscription with no perpetual free plan, though it offers a 14-day free trial that requires no credit card and defaults every account to Premium-level features during the trial period regardless of which plan the user eventually intends to buy. The Standard plan costs $30 per member per month billed monthly, or $24 per member per month if billed annually ($288 per year), and includes pipeline management, email campaigns, contact enrichment, AI assistants, Magic Fields, the folkX LinkedIn extension, email/calendar/WhatsApp sync, access to more than 5,000 third-party integrations (via connectors like Zapier and Make), 500 enrichment credits per month, 2,000 AI field credits per month, and 2,000 messages per member per month. The Premium plan costs $60 per member per month monthly or $48 per member per month annually ($576 per year), and adds custom objects and deals, email sequences, workspace roles, dashboards, API access, and substantially higher usage limits (1,000 enrichment credits, 5,000 AI field credits, 5,000 messages per member, and up to five account syncs per member). An Enterprise tier costs $100 per member per month monthly or $80 per member per month annually ($960 per year) and adds custom usage limits, security controls, group-level permissions, a dedicated account manager with one-on-one onboarding, custom integrations, and priority support. Because pricing scales per member and is recalculated on a prorated basis whenever a new teammate is added, Folk's total cost grows roughly linearly with team size rather than through a flat platform fee, which is a meaningful difference from CRMs that offer a large free tier and then charge for advanced features regardless of seat count.

In the competitive landscape, Folk most frequently positions itself against Airtable and HubSpot in its own marketing and comparison content. Against Airtable, Folk's argument is that a general-purpose database tool lacks native CRM functionality such as email and calendar integration, mail-merge campaigns, email analytics, and contact deduplication and enrichment, all of which are the CRM-specific work Folk was built to remove. Against HubSpot, Folk concedes that HubSpot has a more generous free plan and scales further into enterprise sales and marketing automation, but argues that Folk offers a more modern interface, faster setup, and materially stronger LinkedIn-based contact acquisition through folkX. Other tools frequently compared against Folk include Attio, another newer relationship-centric CRM aimed at a similar audience, as well as Notion-based CRM templates, Streak, and Copper, all of which compete in the broad category of lightweight, flexible CRMs for small teams who find traditional enterprise CRM software too heavyweight. Folk's overall market position is that of a modern, design-forward, relationship-centric CRM optimized for teams whose core workflow is capturing and nurturing a large number of individual relationships (investors, candidates, prospects, partners) rather than running a complex, multi-stage enterprise sales process, which is the segment where its LinkedIn-first capture and AI enrichment provide the most leverage.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '7f48b7ce-b6d6-4a03-9a89-b0fe089765f6';

