-- ── FoodCoopShop ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$FoodCoopShop is an open-source, CakePHP-based ordering and shop management platform built in Austria for food cooperatives, organic shops, and farm shops, available free to self-host or as a paid hosted service.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Open Source / Freemium$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (self-hosted)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2014, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Scharnstein, Austria$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$German$q$, $q$Russian$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$FoodCoopShop Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$FoodCoopShop is open-source software for food cooperatives and local shops. See its features, self-hosting vs hosted pricing, history, and alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$FoodCoopShop is open-source web software for running the ordering, inventory, and payment operations of food cooperatives, organic shops (Bioläden), and farm shops (Hofläden), built primarily for the German-speaking European market but used more broadly. The project was created by Mario Rothauer, a software engineer based in Scharnstein, a small town in Upper Austria, who began building it in May 2014 after founding a local food cooperative of his own, called Fairteiler, and needing software to manage its ordering and distribution process. What started as a tool for a single cooperative expanded quickly: by the end of 2015 it was already in use by four organizations, and in 2016, following a grant from Netidee, an Austrian internet foundation that funds public-benefit open-source and internet projects, Rothauer released the software as open source, opening it up to the wider community of cooperatives that shared the same operational problem rather than keeping it as a private, single-organization tool. From 2018 onward the project's scope broadened again beyond pure member-run cooperatives to also serve commercial bio-shops and specialty retailers, reflecting the reality that many of the ordering, deposit, and producer-communication problems FoodCoopShop solves are shared by any small food retailer working directly with local producers, not just formally structured buying cooperatives.

Technically, FoodCoopShop is built on the CakePHP framework with a MySQL database, and the project provides a Docker-based development environment to lower the barrier for contributors and self-hosters alike; the maintainers commit to constant upkeep with at least one release per year, and as of 2026 the project's GitHub repository shows roughly 119 stars and 22 active contributors, with an estimated 54 separate cooperative or shop initiatives running the software. Functionally, the platform is built around the specific workflows of a food cooperative's ordering cycle: producers and manufacturers get their own login area to manage their own product listings, automatic weekly emails containing PDF order lists are generated and sent to producers so they know exactly what to prepare and deliver, and the system supports a range of delivery rhythms, including weekly, bi-weekly, and monthly deliveries as well as one-off collective bulk orders. A built-in deposit and credit system lets members pay into a running account balance and shop cashlessly against it rather than handling cash at each pickup, which is a common operational pattern for volunteer-run cooperatives that do not want to manage a cash register during limited pickup hours. For shops that also serve walk-in customers, FoodCoopShop supports self-service, in-person shopping with optional barcode scanning at the point of sale, plus integration with physical cash registers and invoice generation for that hybrid retail use case. A network module allows producers who supply multiple food cooperatives running separate FoodCoopShop instances to synchronize their product catalog data centrally rather than updating each cooperative's shop individually, which matters in regions where a single farm or producer commonly supplies several nearby cooperatives at once. The platform also supports multiple languages, including German, English, and Russian, reflecting its use beyond its Austrian home base.

FoodCoopShop's business model mirrors many self-hosted open-source projects aimed at nonprofits and small organizations: the software itself is free to download and run yourself, but Rothauer's team also offers a paid, professionally hosted and installed version for organizations that would rather not manage their own server. The hosted offering carries a one-time installation fee of 1,290 euros including 20 percent VAT, plus an ongoing annual service fee of 619 euros including VAT, and customers can use a domain of their choice, though domain registration itself is billed separately from the installation fee. Support is delivered in person for cooperatives located within roughly 50 kilometers of Scharnstein, and remotely via Skype or, for locations further away, for an additional fee, which reflects the project's roots as a small, personally maintained operation rather than a large distributed support organization. There is no disclosed formal company structure, employee count, or external funding for FoodCoopShop; it operates as an independent open-source project led by its founder with community contributions, funded historically in part by a public Netidee grant and, on an ongoing basis, by hosted-service revenue and any donations the project may receive, rather than by venture capital or a conventional SaaS subscription business.

FoodCoopShop's most direct comparison point is Foodsoft, another open-source, self-hosted platform for managing food cooperatives that emerged from the German food coop movement and is built on Ruby on Rails rather than CakePHP; the two projects solve an overlapping problem for a similar audience and are frequently mentioned alongside each other in community discussions of foodcoop software, though FoodCoopShop's expansion into serving commercial bio-shops and farm shops, plus its point-of-sale and barcode scanning capabilities, gives it a somewhat broader retail footprint than tools built purely around the classic member-ordering cooperative model. Beyond Foodsoft, cooperatives without dedicated software often fall back on manual processes using spreadsheets, generic e-commerce platforms not designed for the producer-communication and deposit-account patterns FoodCoopShop automates, or bespoke local tools built by individual coop tech volunteers, none of which offer the same purpose-built feature set. FoodCoopShop's overall market position is as a mature, community-trusted, niche vertical software project: not a venture-scale company, but a long-running (roughly 2014 to present), actively maintained open-source tool with a real and growing installed base of food cooperatives and small retailers, primarily across Austria and the wider German-speaking world, that need affordable, purpose-built ordering and shop-management software without committing to a large recurring SaaS subscription.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '640f5401-b849-4bad-b457-90e05c828c55';

