-- ── Foodsoft ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Foodsoft is an open-source, Ruby on Rails platform for running non-profit food cooperatives, covering product catalogs, ordering, accounting, and job scheduling, hosted community-wide at foodcoops.net.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Open Source / Free$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (up to 5 user accounts on hosted platform)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2007, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$German$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Foodsoft Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Foodsoft is open-source software for non-profit food cooperatives, covering ordering, accounting, and job scheduling. See its features, hosting, and pricing.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Foodsoft is an open-source, web-based platform built specifically for the operational needs of non-profit food cooperatives, the grassroots, member-run buying collectives common across Germany and much of the rest of Europe where a group of people pool their purchasing power to buy food directly from suppliers of their own choosing rather than through a conventional retail supermarket. The software covers the full operating loop such a cooperative needs: a shared product catalog synced with chosen suppliers, member-facing online ordering, accounting and bookkeeping so the group's shared finances stay transparent, and job or task scheduling, since most food cooperatives run on a work-share model where every member contributes a set amount of volunteer labor (packing orders, managing deliveries, doing the books) in exchange for access to the buying group, and Foodsoft is built to track and coordinate exactly that kind of rotating volunteer responsibility alongside the commerce functions.

Foodsoft's roots trace back to the German food cooperative movement of the mid-2000s; documentation around the project's hosting history references that a hosting collective called 'about:source' ran Foodsoft infrastructure for ten years before that arrangement ended in 2017, which places the software's origins at approximately 2007, making it one of the longer-running pieces of niche cooperative software still in active use today. Developer Benjamin Meichsner has been repeatedly credited as a driving force behind the project's development over its history, and the codebase, written in Ruby on Rails, is maintained as an open-source project under the foodcoops GitHub organization (foodcoops/foodsoft), with a companion project, foodsoft-shop, providing a more modern, React-based webshop front end intended to sit on top of the core Foodsoft backend. The project is licensed under the GNU Affero General Public License (AGPL), version 3 or later, which is a deliberately strong copyleft choice for a web application: because AGPL closes the so-called 'SaaS loophole' in the regular GPL, any organization that runs a modified version of Foodsoft as a network service for others is obligated to make its source code changes available under the same license, not just organizations that redistribute the software as a downloadable package, which reflects the cooperative movement's general preference for keeping shared tooling genuinely open rather than allowing a modified fork to become proprietary while still running publicly.

Unlike a conventional software company, Foodsoft has no formal corporate structure, no disclosed founders in the entrepreneurial sense, no venture funding, and no headquarters; it is a community-governed open-source project whose direction is set collectively, including through monthly community calls where users and contributors can influence the development roadmap directly. What Foodsoft does have, uniquely among the tools in this category, is a shared, centrally maintained hosting platform at foodcoops.net, operated by an IT technology collective called Rokoli, which runs Foodsoft instances on behalf of many separate cooperatives rather than requiring each one to stand up and maintain its own server. That hosted platform's pricing model is deliberately structured to stay accessible to small volunteer organizations: every cooperative gets up to five free Foodsoft user accounts, and only pays a small fee, one euro net per month, for each additional user account beyond that free allotment, meaning a Foodsoft-hosted cooperative's monthly software cost scales directly and modestly with how many active members it has, rather than through a flat platform subscription or per-feature paywall. This pricing structure is essentially a not-for-profit, cost-recovery model rather than a revenue-generating SaaS business, consistent with Foodsoft's identity as infrastructure built by and for the cooperative movement itself.

Because food cooperatives are, by definition, volunteer-run, non-commercial buying collectives rather than businesses trying to maximize revenue, Foodsoft's target audience is narrow but well-matched: existing and newly forming food cooperatives, generally in Germany, Austria, the Netherlands, and other parts of Europe with an active food coop culture, who need shared ordering, accounting, and volunteer-scheduling tooling without paying for or building a custom system themselves. A regional variant, previously tracked in a separate foodcoop-adam repository, existed to serve the Netherlands-based cooperative community before being merged back into the main upstream project, illustrating how the software has been adapted to different national cooperative networks over time while converging back toward a single shared codebase.

Foodsoft's closest comparison point is FoodCoopShop, another open-source, self-hostable platform serving essentially the same category of user, built on CakePHP rather than Ruby on Rails and originating from an individual Austrian founder (Mario Rothauer) rather than a distributed community collective; the two projects are often mentioned side by side in community discussions of foodcoop software, and cooperatives choosing between them typically weigh factors like which platform's hosted service is available in their region, community language (Foodsoft's community skews more toward German- and English-language documentation with a broader pan-European base, while FoodCoopShop is more centrally rooted in Austria), and which feature set better matches their specific ordering and accounting workflow, since FoodCoopShop has expanded further into point-of-sale and commercial bio-shop retail while Foodsoft remains more tightly focused on the classic non-profit, work-share cooperative model. Outside of these two purpose-built tools, cooperatives without dedicated software commonly fall back to spreadsheets, generic e-commerce platforms poorly suited to work-share job scheduling, or bespoke local tooling built by individual technically minded members, none of which replicate Foodsoft's combination of catalog, ordering, accounting, and job-scheduling functionality in one place. Foodsoft's overall market position, then, is not that of a commercial product competing for market share, but of long-running, community-owned infrastructure for a specific non-profit organizational model, sustained by volunteer development effort, a small per-user hosting fee, and the AGPL license's guarantee that the software stays open for the cooperative movement that built it.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '1807f881-55e3-4c8e-81e1-3548278fad9e';

