-- ── Forem ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Forem is the open-source, Ruby on Rails community platform originally built to power DEV Community, offering blogging-forward social features, AI moderation tools, and self-hosting for building online communities.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Open Source / Free$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (self-hosted)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2017, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$New York, New York, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Forem Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Forem is the open-source community platform that powers DEV Community. See its self-hosting options, features, funding history, and top alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Forem is an open-source, Ruby on Rails community platform originally built to power DEV Community (dev.to), a large online community for software developers, before being spun out and generalized into standalone software that any organization can use to run its own blogging-forward social network. The underlying company, now known as Forem and originally incorporated as Dev Community Inc., was founded by Ben Halpern, Jess Lee, and Peter Frank, and its flagship product began life in 2016 to 2017 as 'The Practical Dev' (also referred to as thepracticaldev), before the team settled on the shorter 'DEV' name and, in 2017, formalized the underlying software as its own project. DEV itself went open source as an early milestone in the company's broader open-source strategy, and in October 2020 the company completed a full rebrand from 'the DEV Team' to 'the Forem Team,' with the open-source GitHub repository moving from the /thepracticaldev/dev.to path to /forem/forem to reflect the platform's new identity as generalizable community software rather than a single-purpose developer blog. Forem is headquartered in New York, New York, and raised an $11.5 million Series A funding round led by Mayfield, a venture capital firm based in Silicon Valley, giving the company institutional backing to build out both its flagship DEV community and the broader Forem platform business.

As a company, Forem operates several distinct properties on top of the same core Forem software: DEV itself, described in the company's own materials as the fastest-growing community for software developers, with more than 800,000 registered users and roughly 7 million unique monthly visitors, a scale the company has stated surpasses the monthly traffic of Hacker News; CodeNewbie, a related community and podcast brand aimed at people learning to code; and the underlying open-source Forem platform itself, which any organization can deploy independently to run its own community unrelated to software development. Architecturally, Forem is a full-featured, blogging-forward social network: members publish long-form technical or topical articles written in Markdown, with support for Liquid tags that let authors embed rich content like CodePen demos, GitHub Gists, and YouTube videos directly into a post without writing raw HTML, and the community layer around those articles includes comments, reactions, badges, and gamified achievement systems designed to reward consistent participation. A single Forem deployment is not limited to one community; it supports multiple distinct 'subforums,' each with its own visual identity, moderation policies, and onboarding flow, letting one underlying installation serve several related but separately branded communities at once. On the operations side, Forem includes AI moderation and content tooling backed by Google's Gemini models, covering automated comment quality assessment, article enhancement suggestions, spam labeling, and personalized email digest summaries generated for individual members, alongside a more traditional but still substantial admin toolset: a Blazer-powered analytics suite for querying platform data, a Flipper-based feature flag system for controlled feature rollouts and A/B testing, and Sidekiq dashboards for monitoring background job processing, all of which reflect a platform built and hardened by running one of the internet's larger developer communities at real production scale before being generalized for outside use.

Commercially, Forem's current business model centers on self-hosting rather than a first-party managed SaaS tier: the Forem software itself is entirely free and open source, distributed through the forem/forem GitHub repository, and the company maintains an official self-hosting toolkit, forem/selfhost, along with detailed documentation for deploying a Forem instance on DigitalOcean, AWS, Google Cloud, or bare-metal infrastructure. In an earlier period of the company's history, Forem offered a paid, hosted enterprise tier commonly referred to as Forem Cloud, positioned as a value-added, premium-priced hosting option for larger organizations that wanted priority support and did not want to manage their own infrastructure; however, there is no current evidence of Forem Cloud being actively offered as a commercial product today, and the company's own self-hosting documentation explicitly notes that self-hosted Forem instances come with no SLAs, no managed upgrade path, no enterprise support contracts, and no cloud backup service, meaning organizations that self-host must be comfortable operating their own cloud infrastructure, databases, and command-line deployment tooling without a paid managed alternative currently available from the Forem team itself.

Forem's target audience spans two related but distinct groups: first, developers and general readers who use DEV, CodeNewbie, and other Forem-powered communities as end users engaging with articles, discussions, and each other; and second, organizations, community managers, and technical teams who want to stand up their own branded, full-featured community platform on infrastructure they control, an audience that includes companies building customer or developer communities, media and publishing operations, and niche interest groups who want more ownership and customization than a hosted, closed platform typically allows. In that second capacity, Forem competes with a range of community and forum software spanning very different models: Discourse, a widely used open-source and commercially hosted discussion forum platform; Circle and Mighty Networks, both commercial, fully hosted community-as-a-service products aimed at creators and businesses; and, at a broader level, large closed platforms like Discord and Reddit that host communities without offering the same degree of white-label branding, data ownership, or self-hosting control. Forem's key differentiator within that field is that it is simultaneously proven at genuine production scale, powering one of the larger developer communities on the internet, and available as a completely free, self-hostable open-source project, giving technically capable organizations a rare combination of battle-tested software and full infrastructure control without a recurring SaaS fee, at the cost of having to operate that infrastructure themselves without an official paid support safety net.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '104c1524-087c-4a12-b6f7-1c69780a1d4b';

