-- ── Forgejo ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Forgejo is a self-hosted, community-governed Git forge forked from Gitea in 2022 under the German non-profit Codeberg e.V., offering GitHub-Actions-compatible CI/CD and early ActivityPub-based federation.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Open Source / Free$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (self-hosted)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2022, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$German$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Forgejo Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Forgejo is a free, self-hosted Git forge and Gitea fork governed by the non-profit Codeberg e.V. See its features, licensing, federation roadmap, and rivals.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Forgejo is a self-hosted software forge, a GitHub or GitLab alternative for hosting Git repositories, issues, pull requests, and CI/CD pipelines, that was created in October 2022 as a fork of the popular open-source project Gitea. The fork was driven by a governance dispute rather than a purely technical disagreement: in October 2022, the Gitea trademark and domain were transferred to a newly incorporated for-profit company, Gitea Limited, without prior consultation with the broader community of Gitea contributors who had built the project. When that transfer became public, a group of Gitea contributors signed an open letter asking that the project's trademarks and domains be placed under community, rather than private-company, management; after that request was rejected, those contributors forked the project within weeks under the name Forgejo (pronounced 'for-JAY-oh'), placing it under the umbrella of Codeberg e.V., a German non-profit association that had already been running Codeberg.org, a donation-funded, community Git hosting platform, as an explicit alternative to commercial platforms like GitHub and GitLab.

Forgejo's relationship to Gitea evolved in two distinct phases. It was initially presented as a 'soft fork,' a model the project's own communications compared to LineageOS's relationship to Android, meaning Forgejo continued to track and pull in upstream Gitea changes while adding its own community-governed features and fixes on top. That arrangement ended in February 2024, when the project published a post titled 'Forgejo forks its own path forward,' announcing that Forgejo would become a full 'hard fork,' diverging permanently from Gitea starting after Gitea's version 1.21 and taking sole responsibility for its own codebase going forward rather than continuing to merge upstream Gitea changes. Licensing tells a similarly layered story: the original Gitea code Forgejo inherited remains under the permissive MIT license it always carried, but in August 2024 the Forgejo project moved the overall project's license to the GNU General Public License, a stronger copyleft license, reinforcing the project's community-governance-first philosophy by making it harder for the codebase to be re-privatized the way Gitea's trademark and domain had been. Codeberg.org itself, the flagship community hosting platform under the same non-profit umbrella, migrated its own public instance from Gitea to Forgejo at the end of April 2023, putting real production weight behind the new project almost immediately after the fork.

Technically, Forgejo ships as a single static binary and is deliberately lightweight, documented as running comfortably on as little as 512MB of RAM, which makes it practical to self-host on inexpensive VPS instances rather than requiring the heavier infrastructure some competing forges need. Its feature set covers the expectations of a modern Git forge: pull requests, an issue tracker, a wiki, a container registry, a package registry, Git LFS (large file storage) support, and SSH-based repository access. On the CI/CD side, Forgejo Actions provides workflows compatible with GitHub Actions YAML syntax, letting teams migrating from GitHub reuse much of their existing workflow configuration, with actions resolved by default from data.forgejo.org rather than pulling directly from GitHub, though administrators can configure it to fetch from GitHub directly or from local mirrors depending on their compliance and connectivity needs; all Actions runners are self-hosted, keeping CI/CD execution entirely within an organization's own infrastructure. The project has continued shipping regular numbered releases on an active cadence: version 12.0 arrived in July 2025 and marked the end of life for the earlier v7.0 LTS release series, while version 15.0, released in April 2026 as the project's 100th release, added OpenID Connect token support for Forgejo Actions (letting a workflow request a signed JWT that external systems can verify actually originated from a specific Forgejo workflow with specific claims, avoiding the security risks of long-lived static tokens), a simplified web-based registration workflow for Forgejo Runner, and general usability improvements to issue filtering and the releases list.

The most distinctive long-term technical direction for Forgejo, and one that clearly differentiates it from both Gitea and commercial platforms like GitHub and GitLab, is federation: Forgejo is built around the ForgeFed protocol, an ActivityPub-based vocabulary purpose-built for software forges, with the explicit long-term goal of allowing separate, independently operated Forgejo instances to interconnect the way Mastodon servers federate in the fediverse, eventually supporting decentralized issue tracking, pull requests, and even user identities that are not tied to any single platform or hosting provider. As of the most recent releases, federation is still an incremental, in-progress feature rather than a fully realized capability; the ability to federate repository 'stars' across separate Forgejo installations has already shipped as a foundational first step, but fuller federation of pull requests, issues, and identity remains on the roadmap rather than delivered today. Because Forgejo is entirely open source and self-hosted, there is no company behind it in the conventional sense, no disclosed founding team of individuals, no venture funding, and no single headquarters; it is governed as a community project under the Codeberg e.V. non-profit, and its 'pricing' is simply the cost of the infrastructure an organization runs it on, since neither Forgejo nor Codeberg e.V. sells a first-party commercial hosted tier, though third-party hosting providers and managed VPS platforms do offer paid Forgejo hosting as a service on top of the free open-source software.

Forgejo's target audience is developers and organizations that want a self-hosted, GitHub-like experience while avoiding both the cost of GitHub/GitLab enterprise licensing and the governance risk exemplified by Gitea's own trademark transfer, a concern that resonates particularly strongly with European public-sector bodies, privacy-focused companies, and open-source projects prioritizing data sovereignty and non-profit, community-based project governance over a for-profit vendor relationship. Its closest and most direct competitor is Gitea itself, the project it forked from, and the two are frequently compared feature-by-feature since they still share a large amount of common heritage; broader competitors include GitLab Community Edition and Enterprise Edition, which offer a more expansive built-in DevOps toolchain at the cost of heavier resource requirements, GitHub, the dominant commercial closed-source platform Forgejo explicitly positions itself as an alternative to, and smaller self-hosted forges like Gogs and SourceHut. Forgejo's core differentiation within that field is threefold: nonprofit, community-based governance specifically designed to prevent a repeat of the Gitea trademark situation; a lightweight, single-binary deployment model that keeps self-hosting accessible even on modest hardware; and a genuine, shipping (if still early) commitment to ActivityPub-based federation that no major competing forge, commercial or open source, currently offers at the same level of ambition.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
